{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17413008","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17413008"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T07:50:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T07:50:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261097"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261097"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2403"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505083","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505083"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:25:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:25:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2403"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261097","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1261097"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T07:50:23+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T07:52:04+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":7,"questionsAnswered":6,"marksTotal":6,"marksAttainable":6,"marksAttempted":6,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T07:51:34+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0.17,"questionsCorrect":1,"marksCorrect":1},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"2403","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2403"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.46,0.06,0.31,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2403"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112123"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2403","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2403"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2403"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94188"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1206"},{"type":"tags","id":"1276"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1697"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1704"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45943"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112123","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112123"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 43-year-old woman presents to the GP clinic with a two week history of left-sided lateral thigh pain. The pain is aching in nature and worst when she starts walking or running. The pain is growing progressively worst and at times, it wakes her from sleep. She has not had any trauma, fall or injury to her left hip. She was a competitive endurance runner in her early 30s and now runs long-distance recreationally approximately 4 \u2013 5 times a week.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well and comfortable. Her BMI is 20 kg/m\u00b2. Her vital signs are all within the normal range. There is pain on palpation over the bony prominence of her lateral hip. The pain is worst on all hip movements. Range of motion is normal but limited to pain. The hip exam on the contralateral side is all normal. There is no loss of sensation or muscle weakness in her lower limbs. The rest of her physical examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hip osteoarthritis","Trochanteric bursitis","Meralgia paraesthetica","Iliotibial band syndrome","Femoral neck stress fracture"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is a female runner with lateral hip pain with pain on palpation over the bony prominence of the greater trochanter. This is suggestive of \u003Cstrong\u003Etrochanteric bursitis\u003C/strong\u003E. Trochanteric bursitis is the inflammation of the trochanteric bursae. This is caused by repetitive trauma due to iliotibial band tracking over the bursae. This is common in female runners and the pain may be exacerbated as the patient lie on a lateral decubital position, commonly whilst sleeping.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EConservative treatment for trochanteric bursitis is mainly pain relief (NSAIDs), physiotherapy. Corticosteroid injections have proven efficacy against reducing inflammation and pain in the trochanteric bursae. Surgical management i.e. trochanteric bursectomy is performed if conservative management fails.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis is less likely\u003Cstrong\u003E hip osteoarthritis\u003C/strong\u003E as it commonly presents as hip stiffness with functional-limiting hip pain. Hip movement is typically restricted, with internal rotation commonly reduced early in the disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIliotibial band syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is caused by friction between the iliotibial band and the lateral femoral condyle. This is caused by the iliotibial band to shift and alternate anteriorly and posteriorly across the femoral condyle, leading to iliotibial band tension and inflammation. The pain is predominantly localised over the lateral femoral condyle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMeralgia paresthetica\u003C/strong\u003E is a lateral femoral cutaneous nerve entrapment that causes tingling, numbness and burning sensation in the outer thigh. This is worst when walking or standing, and sitting tends to alleviate the pain. This condition is also more common in obese patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Efemoral neck stress fracture\u003C/strong\u003E occurs mainly in competitive athletes that have a history of overuse and an increase in the intensity of their normal training regimen. This as an insidious onset with an increase in pain during high impact or weight-bearing activities that increase the load on their lower limbs. There may be tenderness along the femoral neck upon palpation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Trochanteric bursitis is a common cause of chronic lateral hip pain in those who do repetitive exercise, such as running."],"references":["Woodley SJ, Mercer SR, Nicholson HD. Morphology of the bursae associated with the greater trochanter of the femur. J Bone Joint Surg Am 2008; 90:284.","Tortolani PJ, Carbone JJ, Quartararo LG. Greater trochanteric pain syndrome in patients referred to orthopedic spine specialists. Spine J 2002; 2:251."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94188"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2403"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94188","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94188"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-25T17:39:49+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-25T17:40:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2403"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112123"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationshi